"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc() function in numpy is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) for x != 0 and sinc(0) = 1. However, due to floating point precision issues, the result of sinc(x) for x != 0 may not be exactly 0, even if mathematically it should be. Therefore, the assertion sinc_result[1] == 0 may fail.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7,8c7,8\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_almost_equal(sinc_result[0], 1)\\n> np.testing.assert_almost_equal(sinc_result[1], 0)\"\n}"